Overview

An example problem

This packages introduces a data set for training purposes, which will be used throughout the tutorial. The data set is called tank and it is a small scale rainwater tank model with enough complexity to highlight some of the key features of this package. The data set can be loaded from the package at any time using the data command: data(tank)

The tank model emulates a domestic rainwater tank system. Rain falling on the roof of the house is captured and directed towards the rainwater tank. Before the rainwater is able to enter the tank the first flush is removed from the start of each storm. This removed amount equates to the first millimetre of water falling on the roof for water quality reasons. The water remaining after the first flush extraction flows into the rainwater tank. Water is extracted from the tank for both indoor (constant) and outdoor (seasonal) use. The amount of water supplied by the tank depends on the current water level in the tank calculated at a daily time step.

A diagram of the system model can be seen below:

The outdoor seasonal demand pattern also responds to the daily temperature (i.e.on hot days, above 28 degrees, the gardener waters more than the seasonal average, but on cool days , below 10 degrees, the gardener waters less than the seasonal average). The tank model simulates each stage of the rainwater capture and use process based on the supplied daily rainfall and temperature time series. The size of both the tank and roof can be varied in the model. Performance is measured according to four metrics:

  • Reliability - the fraction of days on which the full demand could be supplied
  • Volumetric reliability - the total water supplied as fraction of the total demand
  • System efficiency - the amount of water used as a percentage of the water captured by the roof
  • Storage efficiency - the amount of water spilled as a percentage of the water captured by the rainwater tank

Shown below are the performance spaces of two different management options, a contributing roof area of 100 and 110 m2. A comparison of the two performance spaces shows the impact roof area has on the reliability performance metric. A 10% increase in the contributing roof area increases reliability across the space, but the system still responds to changes in climate in a similar way.

The following sections of this vignette will demonstrate how to produce similar plots using the functions of this package.

Creating exposure spaces

This section will introduce the scenarioGenerator function, which is the tool used to take a historical climate record and perturb it to meet required targets. A target might be a specific set of changes for a focussed investigation of one climate variable, or a set of targets that will sample regularly to form a climate space. The function will produce .csv and .Rdata files of data for each scenario, as well as a diagnostic report.

The package provides two techniques for creating exposure spaces; simple scaling and the inverse approach. The simple scaling technique was demonstrated in the above example problem, and while it is a simple technique with limited functionality, it can be a useful first step in examining how a system responds to broad climate stressors. The inverse approach is a much more powerful tool capable of creating stochastic scenarios for more complex changes in climate, like seasonality and storm intensity.

Simple scaling

As mentioned above, the simple scaling technique is somewhat limited in the amount of attributes it can perturb. This is due to the scenario creation method, which as implemented in this package is multiplicative or additive changes to each day. Below is an example rainfall time series of two different scenarios created with this technique, one with 10% less rainfall in the year and the other with 10% more.

Supported attributes

Below are the supported attributes that can be created by simple scaling:

  • P_ann_tot_m
  • Temp_ann_avg_m
  • PET_ann_avg_m

Perturbed spaces

A simple scaled space can be created using four arguments in the scenarioGenerator function. The first is the historical data, obs, which needs to be prepared to meet a specific data frame format. The dates need to be separated into three columns; year, month, day. After the date columns the climate data can be entered in any order, but with the headings P, Temp or PET. An example is shown below:

##   year month day   P  Temp
## 1 2007     1   1 0.0 25.50
## 2 2007     1   2 0.0 24.50
## 3 2007     1   3 0.0 29.75
## 4 2007     1   4 0.0 32.25
## 5 2007     1   5 0.0 32.50
## 6 2007     1   6 4.5 26.50

The second argument is the modelTag. This argument instructs the package on which weather generator blocks to use. For simple scaling cases, this should be set to Simple-ann. Then the specified attributes, which will form each axis, should be included in attSel. As mentioned above, the only supported attributes are annual averages (or annual totals when they apply - as the actions are the same). Finally, the exSpArgs argument is used to control the target sampling.

ExSpArgs is a list, containing type, samp and bounds arguments. The type argument is used to set the type of sampling, which is in this case a uniform grid. This has the tag regGrid. The bounds argument is used to set an axis range for each attribute. Its format is therefore required to be a list, with every attribute in attSel given bounds. The samp argument specifies the number of samples to take inside the bound range, inclusive. So, for example, the following arguments would set up the below exposure space.

modelTag="Simple-ann"

attSel<-c("P_ann_tot_m","Temp_ann_avg_m")

exSpArgs<-list(type = "regGrid",
               samp = c(7,6),
               bounds = list("P_ann_tot_m"=c(0.9,1.5),
                             "Temp_ann_avg_m"=c(-1,4)))

The main function can then be called as shown below, and scenarios will be produced for all of the targets shown above.

scenarioGenerator(obs=obs,
                  modelTag = modelTag,
                  attSel=attSel,
                  exSpArgs = exSpArgs)

Stochastic series (inverse approach)

Creating scenarios with stochastic weather generators is primarily useful in that the pattern of a time series can be changed, while still representing conditions under that climate. This property makes them very useful in a scenario neutral approach, as the whole purpose is to understand how a system responds to future climates. Below is an historical rainfall record compared to a stochastically generated rainfall series, to illustrate how the pattern can change.

With this stochastic data generation, time series can be created with a length longer than historical data, and the inverse approach can be used to target specific changes to the rainfall pattern.

Supported attributes

Below is a list of supported attributes that this package can perturb using weather generators:

  • P_ann_tot_m - an annual total of rainfall (mm)
  • P_ann_R10_m - an annual count of days over 10mm of rainfall (days)
  • P_ann_maxDSD_m - an annual count of the maximum duration of consecutive dry days (days)
  • P_ann_maxWSD_m - an annual count of the maximum duration of consecutive wet days (days)
  • P_ann_P99_m - the 99th percentile day of rainfall (including zero days)(mm)
  • P_ann_dyWet99p_m - the 99th rainfall day of annual wet days (mm)
  • P_ann_ratioWS_m - an annual ratio of winter to summer rainfall
  • P_ann_dyWet_m - the annual wet day average (mm)
  • P_seas_tot_cv - a numeric vector
  • P_mon_tot_cv - a numeric vector
  • P_ann_avgWSD_m - an average of the annual dry spell durations (days)
  • P_ann_avgDSD_m - an average of the annual wet spell durations (days)
  • P_JJA_avgWSD_m - an average of the June-July_August wet spell durations (days) (Same for periods of MAM,DJF,SON)
  • P_JJA_avgDSD_m - an average of the June-July_August dry spell durations (days) (Same for periods of MAM,DJF,SON)
  • P_JJA_dyWet_m - an average of the June-July_August wet day amounts (mm) (Same for periods of MAM,DJF,SON)
  • P_JJA_tot_m - a total of the June-July_August wet day amounts (mm) (Same for periods of MAM,DJF,SON)
  • Temp_ann_avg_m - the average annual temperature (C)
  • Temp_ann_P5_m - the annual 5th percentile temperature (C)
  • Temp_ann_P95_m - the annual 95th percentile temperature (C)
  • Temp_ann_F0_m - an annual count of the frost days (temperature less than zero) (days)
  • Temp_ann_GSL_m - an annual count of the growing season length (NH)(days)
  • Temp_ann_CSL_m - an annual count of the cold season length (SH)(days)
  • Temp_ann_rng_m - a measure of difference between Temp_ann_P95_m and Temp_ann_P5_m (C)

Stochastic spaces

When creating a stochastic exposure space, the same scenarioGenerator function is used, and exSpArgs is constructed the same way as in the simple scaling. The arguments that change are the modelTag and attSel, as well as the addition of attPrim, to control which weather generators are used and with what targets. attSel will now be a lot longer than the simple scaling case, for a few reasons. Firstly there are more changes to climate that can be targeted at once. But the other reason is that there is now a need to specify more attributes as staying constant.

As the pattern is no longer fixed, there are many aspects of climate variables that will change freely, unless specified as a target. Below is an example of a portion of a rainfall time series that has five rainfall attributes overlain. It is easy to see that when only specifying a target change to annual average rainfall many other attributes may also change. If these attributes also change system performance it will be important to hold them constant.

To hold an attribute constant, it can be included in attSel, and then included in exSpArgs but with a sample number of 1. This will tell the package that this attribute isnt to be sampled or included in a space, but held constant as scenarios are created. Additionally, instead of including bounds, the attribute has no range as is kept at historical conditions. Finally, the attributes that should become plot axes can be specified as primary attributes. The primary attribute list should be a subset of attSel, so ensure they are listed in both.

modelTag=c("P-ann-wgen")

attSel<-c("P_ann_tot_m","P_ann_P99_m","P_ann_maxDSD_m")

attPrim<-c("P_ann_tot_m","P_ann_P99_m")

exSpArgs<-list(type = "regGrid",
               samp = c(3,3,1),
               bounds = list("P_ann_tot_m"=c(0.9,1.1),
                             "P_ann_P99_m"=c(0.9,1.1),
                             "P_ann_maxDSD_m"=1))

The scenarios can then be created with the scenarioGenerator function, using the arguments shown above.

scenarioGenerator(obs=obs,
                  modelTag = modelTag,
                  attSel=attSel,
                  attPrim=attPrim,
                  exSpArgs = exSpArgs)

Stochastic spaces continued

In the above example, the exposure space created only perturbed changes in rainfall, and as a result only required one modelTag entry. For multiple climate variables in one space, the modelTag argument will need a model tag for each variable. This package supports multiple options for each variable, as can be seen in the full list below:

  • Simple-ann - for simple annual scaling
  • P-ann-wgen - for a four parameter annual rainfall model
  • P-seas-wgen - for a 16 parameter seasonal rainfall model
  • P-har26-wgen - for a harmonic rainfall model
  • P-2har26-wgen - for a double harmonic rainfall model
  • Temp-har26-wgen-wd - for a harmonic temperature model dependent on wet or dry day
  • Temp-har26-wgen - for a harmonic temperature model not conditional on rainfall

Which model tag is used can restrict the supported attributes to choose from. For example, an annual rainfall model does not support the seasonal covariance attribute (P_seas_tot_cv) as there are no mechanisms for change. The list of supported attributes for each model can be found in the documentation. It should be noted that as the models become more complex they can perturb the climate variables in more ways but will also require more attributes to be held constant.

Below is an example of how to call an exposure space with two variables. There are two model tags provided, and all the attributes for each are provided in attSel. The primary attributes include one from each variable, ensuring that each variable is on the axes of the exposure space. Note that 5th and 9th percentile temperature attributes are also included - this is to ensure the temperature time series keeps the same extremes as the mean temperature changes.

modelTag=c("P-ann-wgen","Temp-har26-wgen")

attSel<-c("P_ann_tot_m","Temp_ann_avg_m","Temp_ann_P5_m","Temp_ann_P95_m")

attPrim<-c("P_ann_tot_m","Temp_ann_avg_m")

exSpArgs<-list(type = "regGrid",
               samp = c(7,6,1,1),
               bounds = list("P_ann_tot_m"=c(0.9,1.5),
                             "Temp_ann_avg_m"=c(-1,4),
                             "Temp_ann_P5_m"=1,
                             "Temp_ann_P95_m"=1))

One at a time testing

Given the wide range of supported attributes, it will be necessary to determine which of these a system is sensitive to. This package provides a simplistic method for doing so, a one at a time scenario creation mode. The goal here is to just change one attribute of a scenario while holding all others constant. All attributes to be investigated should be included in attSel, and exSpArgs can be used to specify the range and interval as shown below:

modelTag=c("P-ann-wgen")

attSel<-c("P_ann_tot_m","P_ann_P99_m","P_ann_nWet_m")

exSpArgs<-list(type = "OAT",
               samp = c(5,5,5),
               bounds = list("P_ann_tot_m"=c(0.7,1.3),
                             "P_ann_P99_m"=c(0.7,1.3),
                             "P_ann_nWet_m"=c(0.7,1.3)))

The above requests would produce the following scenarios, that have been simulated using the tank model demo to show how performance changes.

Mapping performance

Once an exposure space has been created - in that the desired climate scenarios have been generated - the first step is to examine how the system responds. This package has two ways of receiving system impact; the first is to provide an R function that will call the models, and the second is to simulate the exposure space externally, and then provide the impact as an additional data set for the package to finish the plots and diagnostics.

Embedded system model

Providing the system model as a function in R is the simplest way to get the complete bottom up analysis, as the whole process can be automated using the initial function call. Even if the models have been developed in other languages, they could still be executed with an R wrapper function.

The system model function has some required formatting, to work with the generalised structure that is built into the package. The model must accept the same obs input format as the historical data, as scenarios will be produced in the same way. The model must also be a functional, in that it provides one performance value at a time. Given the variations in models across case studies, it is likely that a wrapper function will be needed even if the models are in R, to meet the required format for the package.

The requirements are that the system model has two arguments, the first being a climate data file of the same format as the historical data needed for the package input. The package will produce scenarios to match this format also, allowing for repeat assessment of performance under different climates. The second argument should be a list of any arguments the system model needs. While many parameters can be set in the model, the use of external arguments will allow for easy changes to system operation, design parameters or performance metrics. The final requirement is that the function have one output, the performance value under that scenario. An example function wrapper is shown below:

systemArgs<-list(roofArea=50,                 #System arguments for tank model example
                 nPeople=1,
                 tankVol=3000)

tankWrapper<-function(data=NULL,              #Two arguments, the data file and a list of system arguments
                      systemArgs=NULL
) {
  performance<-tankPerformance(data=data,
                               roofArea=systemArgs$roofArea,   
                               nPeople=systemArgs$nPeople,
                               tankVol=systemArgs$tankVol)
  
  return(performance)                         #Return one value each simulation
}

The system model can then be input to the main scenarioGenerator function using the systemModel and systemArgs arguments shown below:

out<-scenarioGenerator(obs=obs,
                       modelTag=modelTag,
                       attSel=attSel,
                       attPrim=attPrim,
                       optimArgs=optimArgs,
                       exSpArgs=exSpArgs,
                       simLengthNyrs=20,
                       systemModel=tankWrapper, #This argument contains the system model function wrapper
                       systemArgs=systemArgs)   #This contains a list of any arguments the system model needs

External system model

The system response can also be provided manually, if keeping the system models separate is more convenient. In this case, the main package function can be called and will finish at the point of providing a set of scenarios. The output of this first call can then be combined with a system response vector to create the scenario neutral space.

Performance Spaces

Adding context

One of the implications of an exposure space being scenario neutral is that there is no commentary on timings. The space just creates scenarios to represent conditions under a new climate, whenever that climate should occur. To better understand when performance drop offs will occur, other climate science should be incorporated into the approach.
